commentText: Nothing like the topic of roundabouts to get the comments section flowing.  Expats from all over, including this comments section lament how the Spanish don't know how to drive on a roundabout, and even in this video, you got it wrong Stewart.  The reality is that the Spanish do know how to navigate a roundabout in Spain, it is just that it is VERY different to how roundabouts operate almost everywhere else.  The DGT have put up endless information, often contradictory information too.  There is a reason you see Spanish learners in the outside lane all the time, its because that lane has priority.  In Spain the DGT state that a roundabout is just the same as any other road, just that it has a curve.  You must treat it like any curved road, or normal road for that matter.  Whenever you want to change lane, you must give way to vehicles on the lane you wish to enter.  If you wish to exit the roundabout, you may only do so from the outside lane.  You cannot swing across two lanes to exit.  You must enter the outside lane BEFORE you exit the motorway.  In this video, Stewart stated the correct way is to drive into the middle lane.  There is absolutely no reason in this instance to enter the middle lane.  It is easier to stay in the outside lane as you have priority in that lane, and you must be in that lane anyway to be able to exit the roundabout.  This is why you see cars in the outside lane being able to drive the entire way around the roundabout in the outside lane, because they have the right to do so, because its just a curved road, and when they want to exit, they indicate right and leave.  It is cars trying to exit from the middle or inner lanes who cause the problem when they try and exit and drive into the path of a person in the outer lane who is not turning right, but is continuing on the road.  Its a tragically stupid rule of course, it results in seriously reducing the capacity at roundabouts, but that is the rule.

All of these speed limits of course can get lower if a sign says so, so pay attention. 2:00 you did it on the video (not on 11:09) but to clarify, you also have to signal with the right blinker that you are exiting the roundabout, also you can signal with the left blinker to communicate that you NOT exiting the roundabout, but you shouldn't leave it active all the time, only if there are cars that may want to exit. 3:00 best advide, don't drink and drive xD 5:00 locals don't use toll roads cause, at least in Madrid, it doesn't safe more than 15 minutes usually; is not worthy 6:00 you need to have the best accessible from your driver seat, it can't be in the trunk. triangles depends on the visibility there's of your car, if you are in a highway you require to put one behind, if you are in a country road you also need to put one in front; if there's not enough visibility in any of the directions you put the triangles (50 meters at least), you need to place them 100 metes away, if visibility is normal 50 meters away. 8:45 if you get the ticket from the machine, put in the dashboard so it is visible for the pedestrians, otherwise you may get a ticket anyways and later have to present present that you got the ticket in other to avoid paying the fee. Usually now they do it by the license plate, but is better to be safe than sorry. 9:20 sometimes, you can find the sign but there no cameras there; anyway, don't exceed the limit just in case

Many pumps and stations are fully automatic, non-attended by personnel. Most times it's a bit difficult to fiind the right type of fuel as the names are very similar. commentText: I have seen and been told by locals that the Spanish are actually taught to drive around roundabouts in the outside lane. I know people who have been fined by the Guardia for even using the inside lane (some have explained the system to the Police, they get an acknowledgement for the logic, a shrug and still get fined). This may be an Andalusian thing, but the take away is - never assume the person on the outside of you is turning before/with you - there is little indication here and I have had to emergency brake for people going all the way around the roundabout on the the outside lane. Clearly roundabouts are a mystery to many locals, the amount of times I have met locals going around the wrong way or entering from the exit lane, particularly on large or new roundaboutsâ€¦.. I think the take away is be very careful, never assume someone is going to do the logical thing or understands what a â€œglorietaâ€ is or how it even works!

commentText: I've lived in Spain for 8 years (from the UK) and the diversity of junction styles never ceases to amaze me. The most elaborate junctions between a farmers track and a provincial road, roundabouts where one exit is for nothing, dozens of types of junctions with increasing complexity between two roads where really one should just have a stop sign and nothing else, absurdly complex junctions between two motorways where if you get it wrong you are wrong for kilometres, and then, motorways merging with a 70 metre death strip, moments where you have to traverse 4 lanes in a couple of hundred metres. It is truly the wild west of traffic design, sometimes good, sometimes bad, sometimes (often) like the sole objective was to spend money on asphalt and concrete.

commentText: Spain definitely has strict limits for alcohol, even tougher than Canada.  In Canada, the maximum BAC is 80 milligrams per litre or 0.08.  However, most Canadian provinces also have much lower limits, at 50 milligrams per litre BAC 0.05.  In other words, your BAC could be below the national limit, but still get a 1-7 day license suspension if its between 0.05 and 0.08 depending on where the offence is committed.  For example, if Quebec, Manitoba, Nunavut, Northwest Territories, and Yukon, the penalty for going between 0.05 and 0.08 is a 24 hour license suspesnion.  Likewise, its a 3 day suspension in British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan (between 0.04 and 0.08), and Ontario.  Subsequent minor alcohol infractions will result in tougher penalties.  Toughest penalties are in the Atlantic Provinces, namely Newfoundland and Labrador, Prince Edward Island, Nova Scotia, and New Brunswick where minor alcohol infractions result in a 7 day suspension.  For beginner and newly licensed drivers, there's zero tolerance for alcohol use.  No matter where you travel in Canada, if you blow above 0.08, federal and provincial drunk driving laws apply.
